oai_dc:dc.dc:title: University of Denver Men's Ice Hockey Affiliates
oai_dc:dc.dc:relation: Media Relations Records, Athletics and Recreation Photographs
oai_dc:dc.dc:format: 1 item, (photograph), 8 x 10 inches, black and white
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Typed on back: "That championship season ended Monday for the University of Denver. It returned a 1973 second place hockey trophy on order of the National Collegiate Athletic Association as part of a two year suspension penalty imposed by the NCAA over a dispute concerning the eligibility of four DU hockey players from Canada. The suspension was lifted in May, the NCAA wrote it wanted the trophy back, and it was dispatched with farewell glances from (left to right) Hockey Coach Marshall Johnston, Athletic Director Ron Oyer and Acting Chancellor Allen Pfnister. Two of the hockey players involved in the dispute, Brad Carefoot and Ched Miller, played in the national championship tournament."

University of Denver (DU) Pioneers men's ice hockey second place trophy from the National Collegiate Athletics Association Championship in 1973 is admired by coach Marshall Johnston, athletic director Ron Oyer, and acting chancellor Allen Pfnister.

oai_dc:dc.dc:format: 1 item, (photograph), 8 x 10 inches, black and white
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Written on back: "1968-69 NCAA Championship Team, Denver Pioneers." Written on Front (players' signatures): "Murray Armstrong, Tom Gilmore, Al Genovy, Gerry Jonasson, Rich Blanche, Don Thiessen, Terry Leifson, Ed Hamilton, Dale Zeman, Randy Ward, Keith Magnuson, Tim Gould, Craig Patrick, Tom Sampson, Gerry Powers, Bob Trembecky, Jim Wiste, Jim Shires, Cliff Koroll, Tom Miller, Frank Daly."

1967-1968 University of Denver (DU) Pioneers men's ice hockey team poses for a group portrait. Team would go on to become the 1969 NCAA National Champions. Front row (left to right): Gerry Powers, Bob Trembecky, Jim Wiste, Jim Shires, Cliff Koroll, Tom Miller, and Frank Daly. Middle row: trainer Gene Bradshaw, Terry Leifson, Ed Hamilton, Dale Zeman, Randy Ward, Keith Magnuson, Tim Gould, Craig Patrick, and manager Tom Sampson. Back row: Tom Gilmore, Al Genovy, head coach Murray Armstrong, Gerry Jonasson, Rich Blanche, and Don Thiessen.
